library(SMOFA)
library(tidyverse)
library(pheatmap)

1 Spatial data: Simulate an example data set

To illustrate SMOFA we simulate a small example data set with 4 different views and two covariates defining a spatial grid using make_example_data. The simulation is based on 4 factors, two of which vary smoothly along the covariate (with different lengthscales) and two are independent of the covariate. To mimic a situation where we only have incomplete data on the samples we mask 50% of the samples on average per view.

set.seed(2020)

# generate spatial grid and set number of views and samples
sample_cov <- expand_grid(x = 1:10, y =1:10) %>% t()
N <- ncol(sample_cov)
M <- 4

# generate example data
dd <- make_example_data(sample_cov = sample_cov, n_samples = N, n_features = 200, n_views = M, lscales = c(5, 2, 0, 0))
## Warning in if (sample_cov == "equidistant") sample_cov <- seq_len(n_samples):
## the condition has length > 1 and only the first element will be used
# mask some samples in some views
mask <- sample(1:N, N*0.5*M, replace = TRUE)
mask <- split(mask, 1:M)
dd$data <- lapply(1:M, function(m) {
  mdd <- dd$data[[m]]
  mdd[, mask[[m]]] <- NA
  mdd
  })

2 SMOFA

2.1 Create a SMOFA object

To create a SMOFA objevt we need to specify the training data and (optionally) the covariates for pattern detection and inerence of smooth factors. Here, sample_cov is a matrix with samples in columns and covariates in rows. The sample order must match the order in data columns. Alternatively, a data frame can be provided containung one sample columns with samples names matching the sample names in the data.

sm <- create_smofa(data = dd$data, sample_cov = dd$sample_cov)
sm
## Untrained SMOFA model with the following characteristics: 
##  Number of views: 4 
##  Views names: view_1 view_2 view_3 view_4 
##  Number of features (per view): 200 200 200 200 
##  Number of covariates: 2 
##  Number of samples: 100
plot_data_overview(sm)

2.2 Prepare a SMOFA object

Before training, we can specify various options for the model, the training and the data preprocessing. If no options are specified, the model will use the default options. See also get_default_data_options, get_default_model_options and get_default_training_options to have a look at the defaults and change them where required. Here, we drop factors that explain less than 1% of variance in the data starting from 10 factors. We use a grid of 50 points to optimise the lengthscale of each factor and use the moe accurate (though slower) multivariate Z node. To reproduce the results we set a seed for training.

train_opt <- get_default_training_options(sm)
train_opt$drop_factor_threshold <- 0.01
train_opt$seed <- 1234567
model_opts <- get_default_model_options(sm)
model_opts$num_factors <- 10
model_opts$mv_Znode <- TRUE
model_opts$n_grid <- 50
sm <- prepare_smofa(sm, training_options = train_opt, model_options = model_opts)

2.3 Run SMOFA

Now, the SMOFA object is ready for training. Using run_smofa we can fit the model, which is saves in the file specified as outfile. If none is specified the output is only saved in a temporary location.

sm <- run_smofa(sm)
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node Y"
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node Y"

2.4 Down-stream analysis

2.4.1 Variance explained per factor

Using plot_variance_explained we can explore which factor is active in which view. plot_factor_cor shows us whether the factors are correlated.

plot_variance_explained(sm,plot_total = T)

r <- plot_factor_cor(sm)

2.4.2 Relate factors to the covariate

The SMOFA model has learnt lenghtscales for each factor that tell us how smoohtly the factor varys along the covariate. A lengthscale of 0 means that the factor captures variation independent of the covariate, a high value tells us that this factor varys very smoothly along the covariate. In this example, we find two factors that are non-smooth and one smooth factor. Using plot_factors_vs_cov we can plot the factors along the two covariate to visualize this relationship.

get_lengthscales(sm)
##  Factor1  Factor2  Factor3  Factor4 
## 0.000000 0.000000 1.665195 1.309080
plot_factors_vs_cov(sm, scale = TRUE)

More informative is here a plot of the factor values along the spatial coordinates, where we can distinguish smooth and non smooth variation across scace

plot_factors_on_cov_2d(sm, covariates = 1:2)

We can compare this to the factors that were simulated:

df <- data.frame(dd$Z, get_covariates(sm, as.data.frame = T))
df <- gather(df, key = "factor", value = "value", starts_with("simulated_factor"))
ggplot(df, aes(x=covariate_1, y=covariate_2, fill = value)) + 
    geom_tile() + 
    facet_grid( ~ factor) + 
    theme_bw() +
    theme(
      axis.text = element_text(size = rel(0.9), color = "black"), 
      axis.title = element_text(size = rel(1.2), color = "black"), 
      axis.line = element_line(color = "black", size = 0.5), 
      axis.ticks = element_line(color = "black", size = 0.5)
    )

2.4.3 Exploration of weights

As with MOFA(+) we can now look deeper into the meaning of these factors by exploring the weigths or performing feature set enrichment analysis.

plot_weights(sm, factors = 4, view = 1)

plot_top_weights(sm, factors = 3, view = 2)

3 Alternative options and comparisons

3.1 SMOFA with univariate variational approximation

A slightly faster version of SMOFA that is more suitbale for larger sample size can be obtained by setting mv_Znode to FALSE. By this, the model uses a faster, more approximate inference that still uses the information provided by the covariate.

sm_univ <- create_smofa(data = dd$data, sample_cov = dd$sample_cov)
train_opt <- get_default_training_options(sm_univ)
train_opt$drop_factor_threshold <- 0.01
train_opt$seed <- 1234567
model_opts <- get_default_model_options(sm_univ)
model_opts$num_factors <- 10
model_opts$GP_factors <- TRUE
model_opts$mv_Znode <- FALSE
model_opts$n_grid <- 50
sm_univ <- prepare_smofa(sm_univ, training_options = train_opt, model_options = model_opts)
sm_univ <- run_smofa(sm_univ)
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node Y"
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node Y"

3.1.1 Relate factors to the covariate

Again, the SMOFA model has learnt lenghtscales for each factor that tell us how smoohtly the factor varys along the covariate. Here, the factors are slighlty less smooth compared to the training with mv_Znode set to TRUE.

get_lengthscales(sm)
##  Factor1  Factor2  Factor3  Factor4 
## 0.000000 0.000000 1.665195 1.309080
plot_factors_vs_cov(sm_univ, scale = TRUE)

plot_factors_on_cov_2d(sm_univ,  1:2)

3.2 Standard MOFA(+) (without covariates)

When we do not specify any sample covariates or set GP_factors to FALSE, the model falls back to the standard MOFA model. We train this here as a comparison.

sm_nocov <- create_smofa(data = dd$data, sample_cov = dd$sample_cov)
train_opt <- get_default_training_options(sm_nocov)
train_opt$drop_factor_threshold <- 0.01
train_opt$seed <- 1234567
model_opts <- get_default_model_options(sm_nocov)
model_opts$num_factors <- 10
model_opts$GP_factors <- FALSE
sm_nocov <- prepare_smofa(sm_nocov, training_options = train_opt, model_options = model_opts)
sm_nocov <- run_smofa(sm_nocov)
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node Y"
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node Y"
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node SigmaZ"
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node SigmaZ"
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node SigmaZ"
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node SigmaZ"

3.2.1 Relate factors to the covariate

Without covariates (using GP_factors = FALSE), the SMOFA model does not learn lenghtscales for a factor. However, we can still correlate a posterior the covariate to the learnt factors. We note, that these are less smooth than the factors learnt with covariates.

plot_factors_vs_cov(sm_nocov, scale = TRUE)

plot_factors_on_cov_2d(sm_nocov, 1:2)

3.3 Comparison of factor smoothness between models

Compare simulated and inferred factors including the posterior variance of factor values (illustrating the uncertainty of the factor values). Note that factors can be flipped (sign change) and in a different order compared to the simulated factors due to the symmetry of the model.

df <- data.frame(dd$Z, get_covariates(sm, as.data.frame = T))
df <- gather(df, key = "factor", value = "value", starts_with("simulated_factor"))
ggplot(df, aes(x=covariate_1, y=covariate_2, fill = value)) + 
    geom_tile() + 
    facet_grid( ~ factor) + 
    theme_bw() +
    theme(
      axis.text = element_text(size = rel(0.9), color = "black"), 
      axis.title = element_text(size = rel(1.2), color = "black"), 
      axis.line = element_line(color = "black", size = 0.5), 
      axis.ticks = element_line(color = "black", size = 0.5)
    )

plot_factors_on_cov_2d(sm, covariates = 1:2)

plot_factors_on_cov_2d(sm_univ, covariates = 1:2)

plot_factors_on_cov_2d(sm_nocov, covariates = 1:2)
